===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{m|enm|tuft}}, {{m|enm|toft}}, {{m|enm|tofte}}, an alteration of earlier {{m|enm|*tuffe}} (> Modern English {{l|en|tuff}}), from {{etyl|fro|en}} {{m|fro|touffe}}, {{m|fro|tuffe}}, {{m|fro|toffe}}, {{m|fro|tofe||tuft}} (modern French {{m|fr|touffe}}), from {{etyl|LL.|en}} (near Vegezio) {{m|la|tufa||helmet crest}}, from {{etyl|gem|en}} (compare {{etyl|ang|-}} {{m|ang|þūf||tuft}}, {{etyl|non|-}} {{m|non|þúfa||mound}}, {{etyl|sv|-}} {{m|sv|tuva||tussock; grassy hillock}}), from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{m|gem-pro|*þūbǭ}}, {{m|gem-pro|*þūbaz}}; akin to Latin {{m|la|tūber||hump, swelling}}, Ancient Greek {{m|grc|τῡ́φη||cattail (used to stuff beds)}}. Same as {{m|en|tuff}}.

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# A [[bunch]] of [[feather]]s, [[grass]] or [[hair]], etc., held together at the [[base]].
# A [[cluster]] of [[thread]]s drawn tightly through [[upholstery]], a [[mattress]] or a [[quilt]], etc., to [[secure]] and [[strengthen]] the [[padding]].
# A small [[clump]] of [[tree]]s or [[bush]]es.
# {{label|en|historical}} A gold [[tassel]] on the cap worn by [[titled]] [[undergraduate]]s at English universities.
# {{label|en|historical}} A person [[entitle]]d to wear such a tassel.
#* T. Hughes
#*: Several young '''tufts''', and others of the faster men.

